<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&message.id=19784#M19784">67</a> of 454
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 286 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Daryaen wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Massimo_Bertoxx wrote:<BR>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>PvE is great.&nbsp; I enjoy it immensely......I wouldn't still be playing this game after 7 years if I didn't.&nbsp; But there is just no comparison to PvP when the PvP is good.&nbsp; Even the most routine milestones a character can reach on a PvE server can become an accomplishment of epic proportions when done on a PvP server.&nbsp; Nothing compares to the challenge of building a character or a guild and progressing through the game while in direct competition with other players.&nbsp; And nothing compares to the rush of meeting that challenge when you are successful.</P><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Obviously that is personal opinion of course though.&nbsp; I don't see fighting other people to a target to be rewarding, i'd see it more as a hassle.&nbsp; I'm sure to many people, spending money and lots of time to prepare for a raid, getting there, starting it, and getting killed by an opposing gulid, only the lose the target you've waited weeks to kill isn't a lot of fun.&nbsp; And in the grand scheme of things, PvP accomplishments, aside from BotB and ToT never got any notice during EQ's prime.&nbsp; It was always the famous PvE guilds, completeing server firsts that made a mark on the community, and made this game as famous as it is today.&nbsp; </P>
<P>So while you are certainly entitled to your opinion that you find PvP raids far more rewarding, I wouldn't go so far as to say there is "nothing" that compares.&nbsp; Severwide firsts are what made you famous in EQ.<BR></P><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Missed this before so I'm going to respond to this earlier post now...</P>
<P>Of course it's a matter of personal opinion.&nbsp; If you don't find the challenge of PvP fun, nobody is going to force you to play there.&nbsp; I'm not concerned with ToT and BotB tournaments or "making a mark" or "server firsts" or doing anything that "made you famous in EQ."&nbsp; I'm even less concerned when other people do it.&nbsp; I've been playing this game for 7+ years and I have never payed attention to any of that stuff.&nbsp; It's nice to know that a milestone has been reached when it happens, and sometimes there's a really cool story that goes along with it, and my hat's off to those who do them, but that's it really.&nbsp; Fame in EQ and a buck will get you a cup of coffee someplace.&nbsp; I'm interested in good gaming.&nbsp; No more no less.</P>
<P>Just talking about the personal satisfaction that comes from developing a character in the most challenging possible environment....PvP.&nbsp; That piece of gear you got last night on a PvE server that you love was 10x harder for somebody on a PvP server.&nbsp; That raid your guild did last week was 10x harder for&nbsp;a guild&nbsp;on a PvP server.&nbsp; Getting a 1.0 on a PvP server is truely epic.</P>
<P>And the reason is really simple.....PvP is unpredictable.&nbsp; For just about anything you want to do in PvE, you can find a walkthru on how do do it.&nbsp; Look it up on Allas....."Take&nbsp;this number of&nbsp;people here.....Have them do X.....when Y happens make sure the clerics do Z&nbsp;and PRESTO now you have your shiny new Widget of Gnoll Slapping."</P>
<P>In PvP, though the ole formula on Allas doesn't exactly account for the pair of necros who show up and start dropping dots on everybody about the time they start to run out of mana, or the shaman who came with them who starts dropping slows on your melees, or the enchanter that came with them who just mezzes everybody.&nbsp; Allas also doesn't remind you not to forget to bring extra people to kill that group of evils when they enter the zone, or at least alert the raid.&nbsp; Unpredictibility is what it's all about.</P>
<P>And when you get broadsided by something like that, it's just like losing a PvE raid.&nbsp; You dust yourself off, figure out your CR, &nbsp;make note of what you did wrong and plan for the next time....And your revenge on the enemy.&nbsp; WHen you get broadsided by something like that and survive it's really fun.&nbsp; When you get broadsided by something like that and you defend yourself, and still kill that mob you were after, its nothing short of a total rush.</P>
<P>Killing big mobs is great and wonderful.&nbsp; I love raiding in PvE.&nbsp; But I'll say it again, NOTHING compares to meeting the challenge of advancing your toon in the hostile environment of PvP.&nbsp; Nothing.</P>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
